[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":352},["ShallowReactive",2],{"api/learn-center-post-en-leveraged-crypto-trading-risks-and-rewards":3,"footer-en":77,"learn/crypto-trading/leveraged-crypto-trading-risks-and-rewards-en-seo":260,"navigation-en-learn-center":265,"api/learn-categories-en":309},{"seo":4,"locale":23,"breadcrumbs":24,"excerpt":32,"featuredImage":33,"components":40,"title":5,"formattedPublishedAt":52,"geofencings":53,"category":54,"pagination":56,"campaignExternalId":7,"cta":59},{"title":5,"metaTitle":5,"metaDescription":6,"keywords":7,"metaRobots":7,"structuredData":8,"metaImage":9,"metaSocial":16,"canonicalURL":7,"localizations":17},"Leveraged Crypto Trading: Risks and Rewards","Leveraged crypto trading allows traders to increase their purchasing power by using borrowed funds. Learn the risk & rewards.",null,{},{"url":10,"mime":11,"ext":12,"width":13,"height":14,"name":15,"alt":7},"bitstampImageUrl/Leveraged_Crypto_Trading_Risks_and_Rewards_c00ae2897e.png","image/png",".png",900,451,"Leveraged Crypto Trading Risks and Rewards.png",[],[18,21],{"pathname":19,"locale":20},"/es/learn/crypto-trading/leveraged-crypto-trading-risks-and-rewards/","es",{"pathname":22,"locale":23},"/learn/crypto-trading/leveraged-crypto-trading-risks-and-rewards/","en",[25,29],{"id":26,"text":27,"url":26,"asUrl":28},"/learn/crypto-trading/","Crypto trading",true,{"id":30,"text":5,"url":22,"asUrl":31},"leveraged-crypto-trading-risks-and-rewards",false,"\u003Cp>Leveraged crypto trading allows traders to increase their purchasing power by using borrowed funds. While it has the potential to significantly increase profits, it also comes with additional risks. \u003C/p>\n",{"url":34,"mime":35,"ext":36,"width":37,"height":38,"name":39,"alt":7},"bitstampImageUrl/Leveraged_Crypto_Trading_Risks_and_Rewards_a404171568.svg","image/svg+xml",".svg",1920,1081,"Leveraged Crypto Trading Risks and Rewards.svg",[41],{"component":42,"props":43,"content":44,"secondaryContent":48,"ctas":50,"secondaryCtas":51,"ctasNoMarginTop":31},"section.full-text",{"centered":31,"withoutSectionContainer":31},{"text":45,"width":46,"align":47},"\u003Ch2>How Does Leveraged Crypto Trading Work?\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Leveraged crypto trading is the act of taking out a loan to increase a trader’s gains. They operate primarily through a mechanism called margin.  \u003C/p>\n\u003Ch3>Margin Trading\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Put simply, margin is collateral.  \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Crypto exchanges allow traders to borrow funds to increase their purchasing power. These borrowed funds come from a \"margin account,\" which are funded with crypto assets as collateral. This collateral acts as a guarantee for the exchange, ensuring they can recover their funds even if your trade goes south. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>To trade with leverage, an initial margin is required from the trader. As the value of their trades fluctuates, a maintenance margin threshold must be sustained to avoid potential liquidation. \u003C/p>\n\u003Ch3>Leverage Ratios\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Leverage is expressed as a ratio, like 2x, 5x, or even higher. This ratio represents how much the buying power is multiplied compared to a trader’s initial investment. For example, with 5x leverage, a $1,000 deposit lets traders control a $5,000 position. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>This magnification works both ways: \u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Greater profits: If the market moves in the trader’s favor, their profits are multiplied by the leverage ratio. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Amplified losses: If the market moves against them, their losses are also multiplied.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Ch3>Margin Calls\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>The maintenance margin acts as a minimum amount of cryptocurrency traders must maintain in their margin accounts relative to the borrowed funds. If the value of a trader's position drops and the value of their crypto falls below this maintenance margin, a margin call will be triggered. This is a demand to deposit additional funds into the account to restore it above the required level. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Failure to meet the margin call results in liquidation. This means the exchange will sell the trader's assets to repay the borrowed funds, often at a significant loss. Liquidation can wipe out the trader's initial investment and potentially leave them in debt to the exchange. \u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2>Advantages of Leveraged Trading\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Leverage, when used strategically, offers several potential advantages for crypto traders: \u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Amplified gains: Traders can increase their potential profits \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Capital efficiency: Traders can control larger positions than their own capital would typically allow.  \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Flexibility: Leverage can be applied to various market conditions and can be used in bullish and bearish trends, or even in sideways markets with the right strategies.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Ch2>Risks of Leveraged Trading\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Leverage trading can expose traders to several risks: \u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Liquidation and amplified losses: A small price movement in the opposite direction of the trade can quickly erase a leveraged position, and the trader’s collateral might be at risk. This would result in liquidation, where the exchange would remove the trader’s investments, leaving them with nothing. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Volatility: Margin calls are often triggered by volatility against a trader’s position. For example, if a trader expects the price of an asset to appreciate, but the price decreases instead, their entire position would be wiped.  \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Market risk: In the crypto space, traders are always at the whims of adverse news, like negative. regulatory changes, which can cause unexpected price movements.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Ch2>Real-world examples of liquidation risks\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Since the crypto industry is still in its infancy, liquidation events are not uncommon. For example, over the past few years, there have been days where billions of dollars are wiped from the market, including:   \u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>March 2020 crash: The COVID-19 pandemic, and subsequent lockdown, triggered a market-wide crash. This caused over $1 billion in liquidations across various exchanges.  \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>May 2021 correction: Bitcoin's price plummeted over 30% in a single day, and over $8 billion worth of leveraged positions were liquidated.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>Experienced traders can often fall victim to sudden market shifts, especially if they are not well prepared. Without the right tools in place, the increased impact of leverage can turn a small loss into a much more consequential one. \u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2>Risk Management in Leveraged Trading: Strategies to Protect Your Capital\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>There are several techniques traders can employ to protect their capital when trading with leverage, including: \u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Stop-loss orders: Placing a stop-loss order automatically closes a trader’s position if the market price reaches a predetermined level, preventing further downside risk. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Position sizing: Traders determine the appropriate trading size that help them balance the potential profits and losses. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Avoiding over-leveraging: Excessive leverage can quickly lead to liquidation, and traders should use leverage responsibly and within their risk tolerance.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Ch2>Conclusion\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul>\n\u003Cli>Leveraged trading involves borrowing funds to increase buying power and can magnify gains but also significantly increase the risk of losses. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>If a trader's position moves against them and their equity falls below the required maintenance margin, a margin call may occur, potentially leading to liquidation and the loss of their entire investment. \u003C/li>\n\u003Cli>Effective risk management strategies, such as setting stop-loss orders, careful position sizing, and avoiding over-leveraging, are crucial for traders engaging in leveraged crypto trading.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n","full","left",{"text":49},"",[],[],"September 10th, 2024",{},{"title":27,"url":26,"geofencings":55},{},{"previous":57,"next":58},"/learn/crypto-trading/introduction-to-chart-patterns/","/learn/crypto-trading/retail-institutional-and-high-frequency-trading/",{"component":42,"props":60,"content":65,"secondaryContent":68,"ctas":69,"secondaryCtas":76,"ctasNoMarginTop":31},{"sectionId":7,"backgroundColor":61,"paddingTop":62,"paddingBottom":62,"ordering":7,"ratio":63,"centered":31,"containerSize":64,"withoutSectionContainer":31},"Crypto lime","medium","1:1","normal",{"text":66,"width":46,"align":67},"\u003Ch2>\u003Cmark>Ready\u003C/mark> to start your crypto journey?\u003C/h2>\n","center",{"text":49},[70],{"text":71,"url":72,"external":31,"noFollow":28,"type":73,"openModal":7,"downloadItem":74},"Getting Started","/onboarding/register/","Button - Primary",{"file":75},{},[],{"ready":28,"sections":78,"disclaimer":258,"copyright":259},[79,122,145,168,200,219],{"title":80,"content":49,"items":81},"About",[82,87,92,97,102,107,112,117],{"noFollow":28,"isExternal":31,"name":83,"value":84,"isEmail":31,"isPhoneNumber":31,"isText":31,"showOnDesktop":28,"showOnMobile":28,"attachment":85,"geofencings":86},"Who We Are","/about-us/",{},{},{"noFollow":31,"isExternal":31,"name":88,"value":89,"isEmail":31,"isPhoneNumber":31,"isText":31,"showOnDesktop":28,"showOnMobile":28,"attachment":90,"geofencings":91},"The Bitstamp Way","/bitstamp-way/",{},{},{"noFollow":28,"isExternal":28,"name":93,"value":94,"isEmail":31,"isPhoneNumber":31,"isText":31,"showOnDesktop":28,"showOnMobile":28,"attachment":95,"geofencings":96},"Careers","https://bitstamp.workable.com/",{},{},{"noFollow":28,"isExternal":31,"name":98,"value":99,"isEmail":31,"isPhoneNumber":31,"isText":31,"showOnDesktop":28,"showOnMobile":28,"attachment":100,"geofencings":101},"Legal & Privacy","/leg